<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-10-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-10-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="500" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d500">
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extracts.]</seg></opener>
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Clay</persName></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#left">No. 172.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-10-02"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 2, 1865.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have received your despatch of the 5th
                            ultimo, No. 86, relative to the misunderstanding existing between the
                            Russian government and the agent of the American Union Telegraph
                            Company, in regard to the construction to be placed upon the charter
                            obtained from the Russian authorities. * * * * The details of the matter
                            are left to your discretion, but it is expected that you will give it
                            your careful attention.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Cassius M. Clay,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.,&amp;c.,&amp;c.,</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>